I don&#39;t think you can achieve that using sequelize. However, your usecase would typically work better using an inheritance pattern. Think about it, what do Students and Teacher have in common? They&#39;re both human beings, so any attribute that a human being has is common to both.

Here is what I would do:

- Have a model called `Person`, containing all the common properties (first name, last name, birth date...)
- Have two other models, `Student` and `Teacher`, containing specific properties
- Define `one to one` relationships between `Student`/`Teacher` and `Person`. Be careful, you can only define it one way (a `Student` is a `Person` but a `Person` isn&#39;t always a `Student`)
- Define a `one to many` relationship from `School` to `Person`.

That way, you would be able to achieve what you want by doing the following:

```
return School.findAll({
    include: [
        {
            model: Person,
            include: [
                { model: Teacher },
                { model: Student },
            ]
        },
    ],
});
```

And, imho, I believe this model would be more fitting regarding normalization.

